ted. Reaction 17 uses both deoxyadenosine and adenosine as inputs to produce adenine, which is not chemically tidy as a single reaction and does not match a specific prebiotic release pathway well. This branch is more a salvage/decomposition concept than a productive adenine synthesis route.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_014\",\n        \"rxn_017\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Split adenosine and deoxyadenosine hydrolysis into separate reactions\",\n        \"Provide explicit hydrolysis/deglycosylation conditions and plausibility justification\",\n        \"Treat nucleoside formation as an alternative target branch rather than a core route to free adenine unless release chemistry is well supported\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.88,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is a strong, literature-aware adenine synthesis network with excellent redundancy, clear hub architecture, and real convergence on AICN, HCN, DAMN, formamide, and formamidine. It succeeds especially well in reflecting the modern view that adenine synthesis is a network rather than a single linear route. Topologically, it is well connected and includes multiple convergent routes to the target. Chemically, the classical HCN route, AICN/formamidine closure, Hill-Orgel ammonium formate bypass, and formamide-based pathways are all well aligned with the supplied literature. The cyanosulfidic branch is directionally correct and captures high-value recent work, but it is less complete because triaminopyrimidine is not sourced and some conditions are underspecified. The largest deficiencies are formal rather than conceptual: the reaction list as presented omits required mineral-agent specification for hydrothermal and surface reactions, some one-step formamide nodes are over-compressed, and the hydrothermal front-end is the least well supported because vent conditions are generally poor for ade