merization.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.87,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.91,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.89\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.88,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.90,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.91,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.92,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.89,\n      \"feedback\": \"This route captures the literature-supported idea that formamide can feed into HCN-like chemistry, but it is more indirect and somewhat compressed. The network appropriately uses formamide as a feedstock to HCN/formamidine, yet the exact branching from neat formamide to free HCN under surface conditions is system-dependent and not always the dominant experimentally observed route. Still, overall it is defensible.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Differentiate thermal decomposition from mineral-assisted formamide chemistry more clearly.\",\n        \"Add catalyst-specific conditions for formamide decomposition versus condensation.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.87,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.91,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.93\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.88,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.91,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.90,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.93,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.89,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway is conceptually strong because it unifies formamide, formamidine, AICN, and adenine as described in the literature. Its weakness is mostly implementation detail: th