ation in pathway framing.\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.88,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"The network is strong overall and captures the literature insight that adenine is best represented as a convergent network product rather than a single linear synthesis. Topologically it is well connected, with appropriate hubs in HCN, DAMN, AICN, formamidine, and formamide, and it includes multiple convergent routes to adenine. Literature alignment is generally very good for the classical HCN oligomerization, eutectic-freezing concentration, formamide chemistry, AICN centrality, and the high-yield Hill-Orgel route. The main weaknesses are: (1) several reactions are specified too generically relative to the cited literature, especially formamide decomposition and ammonium-formate-to-formamidine conversion; (2) direct hydrothermal adenine formation is overstated given adenine instability in hot vent systems; and (3) the two nucleoside-salvage pathways rely on prebiotic 'biochemical salvage' steps that are not well supported experimentally. Another notable issue is representational: the network summary does not show explicit mineral agents and per-reaction literature citations, both of which were required and matter for full environmental and literature scoring. Because of those omissions and the questionable salvage/hydrothermal adenine endpoints, the network is not quite at approval threshold despite being scientifically sophisticated and largely coherent.\",\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.93,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.94\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_002": 0.94, "rxn_003": 0.88, "rxn_004": 0.87, "rxn_005": 0.91, "rxn_006": 0.95, "rxn_007": 0.93, "rxn_008": 0.89}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.91, "pathway_coherence": 0.95, "environmental_progression": 0.9, "target_achievement": 0.93, "overall_confidence": 0.92, "feedback": "This is the strongest classical adenine pathway