",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 on Fe-S phases gives surface-bound formyl equivalents that are released as formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Included as a conservative hydrothermal feedstock-generating step consistent with Fe-S-catalyzed CO2 reduction in alkaline vent chemistry and the iron-sulfur world framework, supplying C1 precursors that can feed later surface formamide/HCN chemistry rather than claiming robust hydrothermal adenine accumulation (Wachtershauser, 1988-1992; Cody et al., 2000; Saladino et al., 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formamide generation from formate and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-470K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite and magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor rock-water interfaces; condensative amidation treated as a connecting step to literature-established formamide networks\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate/formic acid and ammonia undergo mineral-assisted dehydration to formamide at hydrothermal interfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a necessary connecting step to link hydrothermal C1 chemistry to the experimentally established formamide adenine network. It is more speculative than the downstream formamide chemistry and is included only as a geochemically plausible bridge; the literature report emphasizes formamide accumulation and hydrothermal pore concentration rather than a single canonical synthetic step (Niether et al., 2016; Saladino et al., 2001; Bada & Cleaves, 2015, noting geochemical plausibility remains debated).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface thermal decomposition of formamide to HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373-433K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"drying geothermal or evaporitic settings; based on formamide-HCN equilibrium and mineral-catalyzed formamide condensation systems\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Thermal dehydration/fragmentation of adsorbed formamide yields HCN, which then enters classical oligomerization chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied literature explicitly identifies the equilibrium HCONH2 \u21cc HCN + H2O and notes that formamide chemistry proceeds through HCN-like intermediates. This reaction is used to connect the validated formamide and HCN sub-networks while keeping mineral agents explicit for the surface setting (Saladino et al., 2001; Barks et al., 2010; Yamada et al., 1978; Slavova et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical HCN dimerization to iminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"293-343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite concentrating surface with alkaline phosphate-buffered microenvironments\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8-9, concentrated NH4CN/HCN solution or evaporative concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CN- attacks HCN in a base-catalyzed dimerization to form the HCN dimer iminoacetonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the first mechanistic step of the Or\u00f3/Sanchez-Ferris-Orgel oligomerization sequence. The dimer is computationally validated though not isolated from aqueous HCN; pH 8-9 is optimal because HCN and CN- coexist. Mineral surfaces are included as concentration/organization aids in surface settings (Oro, 1960; Sanchez et al., 1967; Kikuchi et al., 2000; Sandstrom & Rahm, 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN trimerization to aminomalononitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"293-343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and phosphate-rich evaporitic surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8-9, concentrated cyanide solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Addition of a third HCN equivalent to the HCN dimer yields the highly reactive trimer aminomalononitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This follows the classical pentamerization sequence and is supported by mechanistic/computational studies and the Sanchez-Ferris-Orgel framework for HCN polymerization (Sanchez et al., 1967; Roy et al., 2007; Sandstrom & Rahm, 2025/2026).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN tetramerization to DAMN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"293-343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and phosphate-buffered concentrating environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8-9; DAMN isolable under concentrated NH4CN chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Addition of the fourth HCN equivalent gives diaminomaleonitrile, the first stable isolable tetramer.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"DAMN is a key experimentally observed HCN tetramer and pivotal stable intermediate in adenine chemistry. Its formation from concentrated HCN/NH4CN is foundational to the adenine network (Zubay & Mui, 2001; Oro, 1960; Sandstrom & Rahm, 2025/2026).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photoisomerization of DAMN to trans-DAMN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"273-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalytic surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV 298-350 nm, anoxic young-Sun irradiation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photons drive cis/trans isomerization of DAMN to the trans isomer (DAFN), initiating the multistep photochemical route to AICN.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ferris and Orgel established UV-driven DAMN photoisomerization; Michaelian and Simeonov quantified rapid AICN formation under young-Sun UV. TiO2 is included as the required surface mineral photocatalyst, consistent with UV-assisted surface photochemistry, though the core photochemistry is intrinsic to DAMN itself (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Michaelian & Simeonov, 2022; Senanayake & Idriss, 2006).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Photochemical conversion of trans-DAMN to AICN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"273-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalytic surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV 298-350 nm; ketenimine-mediated photorearrangement\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Further UV excitation rearranges trans-DAMN through ketenimine-like intermediates to 4-aminoimidazole-5-carbonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"AICN is the central hub of prebiotic purine synthesis. The trans-DAMN to AICN photorearrangement is directly supported by the Ferris-Orgel pathway and later photochemical analysis showing substantial AICN production under plausible UV flux (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Michaelian & Simeonov, 2022; Sanchez et al., 1968).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"AICN ring closure with HCN to adenine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"293-343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration surface; NH3-catalyzed bulk-water closure\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8-9, NH3 present; kinetically bottlenecked step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"AICN reacts with a fifth HCN equivalent to form the purine pyrimidine ring, yielding adenine after cyclization and tautomerization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the canonical final step of classical HCN pentamerization. The literature identifies it as the kinetic bottleneck, with NH3 catalysis sharply lowering the barrier. Mineral surfaces are included here as concentration aids in evaporitic pools, not as a claim of a distinct mineral-specific catalytic mechanism (Sanchez et al., 1968; Roy et al., 2007; Armas-Vazquez et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal conversion of HCN-derived intermediates to formamidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343-383K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite concentrating dry-down surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic concentration; formamidine detected in HCN oligomerization mixtures\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia-assisted conversion within concentrated HCN oligomerization mixtures furnishes formamidine as a one-carbon/one-nitrogen donor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research report explicitly identifies formamidine as detected in HCN oligomerization mixtures and as the alternative donor for AICN cyclization. This step is represented as a mixture-level productive node connecting classical HCN chemistry to the Sanchez-Ferris-Orgel branch chemistry (Sanchez et al., 1968; Zubay & Mui, 2001; Hill & Orgel, 2002).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"AICN ring closure with formamidine to adenine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"333-383K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite drying surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"warm evaporitic or wet-dry cycling regime\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formamidine supplies the C-2/N fragment for cyclocondensation with AICN to close the purine ring and generate adenine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the established alternative terminal branch from the AICN hub and is specifically highlighted in Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel's work and in later summaries of the AICN-centered purine network (Sanchez et al., 1968; Zubay & Mui, 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Formation of ammonium formate from formic acid and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"293-333K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"salt-forming evaporitic mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporation-driven concentration in surface pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acid-base neutralization and evaporation concentrate ammonium formate as a reactive salt for subsequent thermolysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hill & Orgel used ammonium formate as the productive additive in the highest-yield one-pot prebiotic adenine route from DAMN. This step formalizes its acquisition from plausible prebiotic feedstocks in a surface evaporitic setting (Hill & Orgel, 2002; Pearce et al., 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermolysis of ammonium formate to formamidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"383K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"heated mineral-rich dry film\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"110C dry heating; in situ donor generation in Hill-Orgel regime\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Heating ammonium formate generates formamidine in situ, enabling subsequent cyclization chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research report explicitly states that ammonium formate can substitute for formamidine because it converts to formamidine in situ under the Hill-Orgel conditions. This is the key bridge between the salt and the productive cyclization donor (Hill & Orgel, 2002).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hill-Orgel adenine synthesis from DAMN and ammonium formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"383K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"heated dry mineral film\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"110C, one-pot route bypassing explicit UV step; ~18% yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Upon heating, ammonium formate generates formamidine-like reactive species in situ, allowing DAMN to cyclize through a bypass route to adenine without requiring the photochemical DAMN-to-AICN sequence as an isolated step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the best-yielding prebiotically plausible one-pot adenine synthesis in the supplied literature and must be represented explicitly. It bypasses the need to isolate the photochemical AICN route and gives ~18% adenine at 110C (Hill & Orgel, 2002).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Mineral-catalyzed formamide condensation to adenine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373-433K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 anatase or montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"neat formamide; 100-160C; one-pot nucleobase synthesis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensed formamide undergoes thermally driven self-catalytic decomposition and recombination via HCN-like intermediates to furnish adenine in one pot.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Saladino and coworkers showed that heating neat formamide with mineral catalysts such as TiO2 and montmorillonite yields adenine among the canonical nucleobases. This pathway is experimentally validated and distinct from the explicit stepwise HCN route, even though mechanistically it passes through related intermediates (Saladino et al., 2001; Saladino et al., 2003; Saladino et al., 2004; Slavova et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Iron-sulfur mineral-catalyzed formamide condensation to adenine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"433K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite-rich iron-sulfur mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"160C interfacial/mineral-rich formamide chemistry; included cautiously because adenine stability at hotter vents is poor\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fe-S mineral surfaces catalyze formamide condensation through radical/condensation chemistry analogous to the broader formamide nucleobase network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyrite/pyrrhotite-catalyzed formamide condensation to purines is directly supported, but this node is treated cautiously as a localized mineral-assisted production step rather than evidence for sustained hydrothermal adenine accumulation, in line with the supplied warning about adenine instability at elevated hydrothermal temperatures (Saladino et al., 2008; Levy & Miller, 1998; Franiatte et al., 2008).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical Or\u00f3 pentamerization route\",\n      \"description\": \"Canonical HCN oligomerization in concentrated surface cyanide solutions progressing through dimer, trimer, DAMN, UV-driven AICN, then closure with HCN to adenine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"AICN-formamidine closure route\",\n      \"description\": \"Classical HCN oligomerization to AICN followed by the Sanchez-Ferris-Orgel branch using formamidine instead of HCN for the final ring closure.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hill-Orgel DAMN plus ammonium formate route\",\n      \"description\": \"High-yield one-pot dry-heating route in which HCN oligomerization furnishes DAMN and surface-generated ammonium formate enables direct adenine formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hill-Orgel via explicit in situ formamidine generation\",\n      \"description\": \"Variant of the ammonium formate route made explicit by thermolysis to formamidine before productive cyclization chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface formamide then direct mineral condensation\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction supplies formate and formamide, which are transported to surface mineral settings where neat-formamide condensation yields adenine directly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface formamide-to-HCN classical route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal generation of formamide feeds surface decomposition to HCN, which then follows the full classical photochemical AICN route to adenine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface formamide-to-HCN formamidine branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Same cross-environment handoff as P6, but the final AICN closure uses formamidine generated in the HCN mixture.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formamide direct adenine synthesis on TiO2\",\n      \"description\": \"One-pot adenine synthesis from neat formamide under surface heating on TiO2-rich mineral assemblages.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formamide direct adenine synthesis on montmorillonite\",\n      \"description\": \"One-pot adenine synthesis from neat formamide on clay-rich surfaces, representing the montmorillonite-supported branch of the same validated formamide chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Localized iron-sulfur formamide condensation route\",\n      \"description\": \"Cautious hydrothermal/interfacial branch in which iron-sulfur minerals catalyze formamide condensation to adenine under the Saladino iron-sulfur conditions.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_007\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Adenine", "overall_strategy": "This network models adenine as a convergent prebiotic product arising from multiple literature-supported entry points that feed a shared HCN/AICN-centered reaction graph. Hydrothermal chemistry is used conservatively as a source of reduced C1 feedstocks and formamide precursors rather than as the main adenine accumulation setting, consistent with adenine instability at high temperature. Surface environments provide the dominant productive chemistry through classical HCN oligomerization, eutectic concentration, UV-driven DAMN photoisomerization to AICN, Hill-Orgel ammonium-formate-mediated cyclization, and mineral-catalyzed formamide condensation. Biochemical/prebiotic settings are limited to assembly-level transformations already grounded in the supplied literature, avoiding unsupported nucleoside-to-adenine salvage. Ten distinct pathways are represented as different valid routes through the same connected bipartite graph, with HCN, DAMN, AICN, formamide, and formamidine serving as hubs.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCOOH", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "HCONH2", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH2N2", "iupac_name": "methanimidamide", "common_name": "formamidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4N2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H3,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H2N2", "iupac_name": "2-iminoacetonitrile", "common_name": "iminoacetonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2N2/c3-1-2-4/h2H", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H3N3", "iupac_name": "2-aminoprop-1-ene-1,1,3-tricarbonitrile", "common_name": "aminomalononitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C4H4N4", "iupac_name": "2,3-diaminobut-2-enedinitrile", "common_name": "diaminomaleonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4N4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h7-8H,1-2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C4H4N4", "iupac_name": "2,3-diaminofumaronitrile", "common_name": "trans-DAMN / DAFN", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H3N5", "iupac_name": "4-amino-1H-imidazole-5-carbonitrile", "common_name": "AICN", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "CH5NO2", "iupac_name": "ammonium formate", "common_name": "ammonium formate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H5N5", "iupac_name": "9H-purin-6-amine", "common_name": "adenine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H5N5/c6-5-4(8-2-7)3-9-1-10-5/h1-3H,(H2,6,7,8,9,10)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 on Fe-S phases gives surface-bound formyl equivalents that are released as formate.", "reasoning": "Included as a conservative hydrothermal feedstock-generating step consistent with Fe-S-catalyzed CO2 reduction in alkaline vent chemistry and the iron-sulfur world framework, supplying C1 precursors that can feed later surface formamide/HCN chemistry rather than claiming robust hydrothermal adenine accumulation (Wachtershauser, 1988-1992; Cody et al., 2000; Saladino et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal formamide generation from formate and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_015"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-470K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite and magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor rock-water interfaces; condensative amidation treated as a connecting step to literature-established formamide networks"}, "mechanism": "Formate/formic acid and ammonia undergo mineral-assisted dehydration to formamide at hydrothermal interfaces.", "reasoning": "This is a necessary connecting step to link hydrothermal C1 chemistry to the experimentally established formamide adenine network. It is more speculative than the downstream formamide chemistry and is included only as a geochemically plausible bridge; the literature report emphasizes formamide accumulation and hydrothermal pore concentration rather than a single canonical synthetic step (Niether et al., 2016; Saladino et al., 2001; Bada & Cleaves, 2015, noting geochemical plausibility remains debated)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface thermal decomposition of formamide to HCN", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373-433K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and montmorillonite", "aqueous": "false", "other": "drying geothermal or evaporitic settings; based on formamide-HCN equilibrium and mineral-catalyzed formamide condensation systems"}, "mechanism": "Thermal dehydration/fragmentation of adsorbed formamide yields HCN, which then enters classical oligomerization chemistry.", "reasoning": "The supplied literature explicitly identifies the equilibrium HCONH2 \u21cc HCN + H2O and notes that formamide chemistry proceeds through HCN-like intermediates. This reaction is used to connect the validated formamide and HCN sub-networks while keeping mineral agents explicit for the surface setting (Saladino et al., 2001; Barks et al., 2010; Yamada et al., 1978; Slavova et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Classical HCN dimerization to iminoacetonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "293-343K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite concentrating surface with alkaline phosphate-buffered microenvironments", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8-9, concentrated NH4CN/HCN solution or evaporative concentration"}, "mechanism": "CN- attacks HCN in a base-catalyzed dimerization to form the HCN dimer iminoacetonitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the first mechanistic step of the Or\u00f3/Sanchez-Ferris-Orgel oligomerization sequence. The dimer is computationally validated though not isolated from aqueous HCN; pH 8-9 is optimal because HCN and CN- coexist. Mineral surfaces are included as concentration/organization aids in surface settings (Oro, 1960; Sanchez et al., 1967; Kikuchi et al., 2000; Sandstrom & Rahm, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "HCN trimerization to aminomalononitrile", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "293-343K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and phosphate-rich evaporitic surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8-9, concentrated cyanide solution"}, "mechanism": "Addition of a third HCN equivalent to the HCN dimer yields the highly reactive trimer aminomalononitrile.", "reasoning": "This follows the classical pentamerization sequence and is supported by mechanistic/computational studies and the Sanchez-Ferris-Orgel framework for HCN polymerization (Sanchez et al., 1967; Roy et al., 2007; Sandstrom & Rahm, 2025/2026)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "HCN tetramerization to DAMN", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "293-343K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and phosphate-buffered concentrating environment", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8-9; DAMN isolable under concentrated NH4CN chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Addition of the fourth HCN equivalent gives diaminomaleonitrile, the first stable isolable tetramer.", "reasoning": "DAMN is a key experimentally observed HCN tetramer and pivotal stable intermediate in adenine chemistry. Its formation from concentrated HCN/NH4CN is foundational to the adenine network (Zubay & Mui, 2001; Oro, 1960; Sandstrom & Rahm, 2025/2026)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "UV photoisomerization of DAMN to trans-DAMN", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "273-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalytic surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV 298-350 nm, anoxic young-Sun irradiation"}, "mechanism": "Photons drive cis/trans isomerization of DAMN to the trans isomer (DAFN), initiating the multistep photochemical route to AICN.", "reasoning": "Ferris and Orgel established UV-driven DAMN photoisomerization; Michaelian and Simeonov quantified rapid AICN formation under young-Sun UV. TiO2 is included as the required surface mineral photocatalyst, consistent with UV-assisted surface photochemistry, though the core photochemistry is intrinsic to DAMN itself (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Michaelian & Simeonov, 2022; Senanayake & Idriss, 2006)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Photochemical conversion of trans-DAMN to AICN", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "273-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalytic surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV 298-350 nm; ketenimine-mediated photorearrangement"}, "mechanism": "Further UV excitation rearranges trans-DAMN through ketenimine-like intermediates to 4-aminoimidazole-5-carbonitrile.", "reasoning": "AICN is the central hub of prebiotic purine synthesis. The trans-DAMN to AICN photorearrangement is directly supported by the Ferris-Orgel pathway and later photochemical analysis showing substantial AICN production under plausible UV flux (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Michaelian & Simeonov, 2022; Sanchez et al., 1968)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "AICN ring closure with HCN to adenine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "293-343K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration surface; NH3-catalyzed bulk-water closure", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8-9, NH3 present; kinetically bottlenecked step"}, "mechanism": "AICN reacts with a fifth HCN equivalent to form the purine pyrimidine ring, yielding adenine after cyclization and tautomerization.", "reasoning": "This is the canonical final step of classical HCN pentamerization. The literature identifies it as the kinetic bottleneck, with NH3 catalysis sharply lowering the barrier. Mineral surfaces are included here as concentration aids in evaporitic pools, not as a claim of a distinct mineral-specific catalytic mechanism (Sanchez et al., 1968; Roy et al., 2007; Armas-Vazquez et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Thermal conversion of HCN-derived intermediates to formamidine", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343-383K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite concentrating dry-down surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic concentration; formamidine detected in HCN oligomerization mixtures"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia-assisted conversion within concentrated HCN oligomerization mixtures furnishes formamidine as a one-carbon/one-nitrogen donor.", "reasoning": "The deep research report explicitly identifies formamidine as detected in HCN oligomerization mixtures and as the alternative donor for AICN cyclization. This step is represented as a mixture-level productive node connecting classical HCN chemistry to the Sanchez-Ferris-Orgel branch chemistry (Sanchez et al., 1968; Zubay & Mui, 2001; Hill & Orgel, 2002)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "AICN ring closure with formamidine to adenine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "333-383K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite drying surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "warm evaporitic or wet-dry cycling regime"}, "mechanism": "Formamidine supplies the C-2/N fragment for cyclocondensation with AICN to close the purine ring and generate adenine.", "reasoning": "This is the established alternative terminal branch from the AICN hub and is specifically highlighted in Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel's work and in later summaries of the AICN-centered purine network (Sanchez et al., 1968; Zubay & Mui, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Formation of ammonium formate from formic acid and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "293-333K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "salt-forming evaporitic mineral surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporation-driven concentration in surface pools"}, "mechanism": "Acid-base neutralization and evaporation concentrate ammonium formate as a reactive salt for subsequent thermolysis.", "reasoning": "Hill & Orgel used ammonium formate as the productive additive in the highest-yield one-pot prebiotic adenine route from DAMN. This step formalizes its acquisition from plausible prebiotic feedstocks in a surface evaporitic setting (Hill & Orgel, 2002; Pearce et al., 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Thermolysis of ammonium formate to formamidine", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "383K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "heated mineral-rich dry film", "aqueous": "false", "other": "110C dry heating; in situ donor generation in Hill-Orgel regime"}, "mechanism": "Heating ammonium formate generates formamidine in situ, enabling subsequent cyclization chemistry.", "reasoning": "The deep research report explicitly states that ammonium formate can substitute for formamidine because it converts to formamidine in situ under the Hill-Orgel conditions. This is the key bridge between the salt and the productive cyclization donor (Hill & Orgel, 2002)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Hill-Orgel adenine synthesis from DAMN and ammonium formate", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "383K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "heated dry mineral film", "aqueous": "false", "other": "110C, one-pot route bypassing explicit UV step; ~18% yield"}, "mechanism": "Upon heating, ammonium formate generates formamidine-like reactive species in situ, allowing DAMN to cyclize through a bypass route to adenine without requiring the photochemical DAMN-to-AICN sequence as an isolated step.", "reasoning": "This is the best-yielding prebiotically plausible one-pot adenine synthesis in the supplied literature and must be represented explicitly. It bypasses the need to isolate the photochemical AICN route and gives ~18% adenine at 110C (Hill & Orgel, 2002)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Mineral-catalyzed formamide condensation to adenine", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373-433K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 anatase or montmorillonite", "aqueous": "false", "other": "neat formamide; 100-160C; one-pot nucleobase synthesis"}, "mechanism": "Condensed formamide undergoes thermally driven self-catalytic decomposition and recombination via HCN-like intermediates to furnish adenine in one pot.", "reasoning": "Saladino and coworkers showed that heating neat formamide with mineral catalysts such as TiO2 and montmorillonite yields adenine among the canonical nucleobases. This pathway is experimentally validated and distinct from the explicit stepwise HCN route, even though mechanistically it passes through related intermediates (Saladino et al., 2001; Saladino et al., 2003; Saladino et al., 2004; Slavova et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Iron-sulfur mineral-catalyzed formamide condensation to adenine", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "433K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "pyrite-rich iron-sulfur mineral surface", "aqueous": "false", "other": "160C interfacial/mineral-rich formamide chemistry; included cautiously because adenine stability at hotter vents is poor"}, "mechanism": "Fe-S mineral surfaces catalyze formamide condensation through radical/condensation chemistry analogous to the broader formamide nucleobase network.", "reasoning": "Pyrite/pyrrhotite-catalyzed formamide condensation to purines is directly supported, but this node is treated cautiously as a localized mineral-assisted production step rather than evidence for sustained hydrothermal adenine accumulation, in line with the supplied warning about adenine instability at elevated hydrothermal temperatures (Saladino et al., 2008; Levy & Miller, 1998; Franiatte et al., 2008)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Classical Or\u00f3 pentamerization route", "description": "Canonical HCN oligomerization in concentrated surface cyanide solutions progressing through dimer, trimer, DAMN, UV-driven AICN, then closure with HCN to adenine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_010", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "AICN-formamidine closure route", "description": "Classical HCN oligomerization to AICN followed by the Sanchez-Ferris-Orgel branch using formamidine instead of HCN for the final ring closure.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hill-Orgel DAMN plus ammonium formate route", "description": "High-yield one-pot dry-heating route in which HCN oligomerization furnishes DAMN and surface-generated ammonium formate enables direct adenine formation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_012", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_010", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hill-Orgel via explicit in situ formamidine generation", "description": "Variant of the ammonium formate route made explicit by thermolysis to formamidine before productive cyclization chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_007", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-surface formamide then direct mineral condensation", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction supplies formate and formamide, which are transported to surface mineral settings where neat-formamide condensation yields adenine directly.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_015"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-surface formamide-to-HCN classical route", "description": "Hydrothermal generation of formamide feeds surface decomposition to HCN, which then follows the full classical photochemical AICN route to adenine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-surface formamide-to-HCN formamidine branch", "description": "Same cross-environment handoff as P6, but the final AICN closure uses formamidine generated in the HCN mixture.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_007", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Surface formamide direct adenine synthesis on TiO2", "description": "One-pot adenine synthesis from neat formamide under surface heating on TiO2-rich mineral assemblages.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_0